- [F-003-01] The strongest adoption target is not Gem Team’s JSON file itself; it is the dispatch-time invariant that every subagent starts from the same curated snapshot. Gem Team makes that explicit with `context_envelope_snapshot` [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/AGENTS.md:21], while Spec Kit currently synthesizes Context Packages but does not require all leaf agents to receive the same snapshot [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/context.md:230].
- [F-003-02] Spec Kit already has a stronger durable continuity substrate than Gem Team: packet docs are canonical, recovery starts with `handover.md -> _memory.continuity -> spec docs` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/memory_system.md:16], and the active packet has `_memory.continuity` with recent action, next action, blockers, and key files [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/spec.md:21].
- [F-003-03] Gem Team’s progressive enrichment is concrete and useful: the orchestrator merges learnings, promotes recurrent signals, and delegates envelope update [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/.apm/agents/gem-orchestrator.agent.md:131]. Spec Kit equivalent is `/memory:save` / `generate-context.js`, which updates continuity surfaces and reindexes docs [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/save_workflow.md:156].
- [F-003-04] Do not adopt Gem Team’s envelope as a replacement source of truth. Spec Kit explicitly says packet docs outrank memory search for runtime truth [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/context.md:96], and `generate-context.js` refreshes graph metadata as part of canonical saves [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/memory/generate-context.ts:84].
- [F-003-05] Best adaptation: add an optional “context envelope snapshot” layer on top of existing Context Packages for multi-agent waves, populated from `handover.md`, `_memory.continuity`, spec docs, memory_context, and resource-map. That preserves Spec Kit’s file-distributed continuity [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/context.md:162] while borrowing Gem Team’s consistent subagent handoff [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/README.md:94].

### NEGATIVE / RULED-OUT
Strict single JSON as the canonical continuity store is ruled out. Our equivalent is the canonical recovery ladder and packet-doc truth model: `handover.md`, `_memory.continuity`, then spec docs [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/save_workflow.md:313] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/memory/save_workflow.md:315].
Strict “subagents never touch memory” is ruled out. Our equivalent is central exploration through @context plus scoped memory tools when packet-local continuity leaves gaps [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/context.md:34] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/context.md:171].
Separate race-control cache is ruled out. Our equivalent is canonical save locking plus atomic phase-parent metadata update [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/memory/generate-context.ts:405] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/memory/generate-context.ts:490].

### OPEN QUESTIONS
Should `@orchestrate` require a Context Package snapshot in every multi-agent wave dispatch?
Should the snapshot be transient in the dispatch prompt only, or persisted as a packet-local generated support artifact?
Should resource-map entries grow optional reread directives, or should those live only in the Context Package?

